07366nam a22009495i 9781478009313DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019055648  a97814780093137 a10.1515/97814780093132doi  a(DE-B1597)551996  a(OCoLC)1198932092  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC00aPN1590.S6 4aPN1590.S6bR34 2020 7aPER0110202bisacsh04a79122300aRace and Performance after Repetition /ced. by Soyica Diggs Colbert, Shane Vogel, Douglas A. Jones Jr. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Tidying Up after Repetition -- tPART I. TOGGLING TIME: METATHEATERS OF RACE -- t1 So Far Down You Can't See the Light: Afro-Fabulation in Branden Jacobs-Jenkins's An Octoroon -- t2 The Performance and Politics of Concurrent Temporalities in George C. Wolfe's Shuffle Along -- t3 A Sonic Treatise of Futurity: Universes' Party People -- tPART II. CHOREO-CHRONOGRAPHIES -- t4 Joe Louis's Utopic Glitch -- t5 Sorrow's Swing -- t6 Parabolic Moves: Time, Narrative, and Difference in New Circus -- t7 Choreographing Time Travel: Rethinking Ritual through Korean Diasporic Performance -- tPART III. TEMPORAL (IM)MOBILITIES DWELLING OUT OF TIME -- t8 Carceral Space-Times and The House That Herman Built -- t9 Performance Interventions: Natality and Carceral Feminism in Contemporary India -- t10 Witnessing Queer Flights: Josué Azor's Lougawou Images and Antihomosexual Unrest in -- t11 The Body Is Never Given, nor Do We Actually See It -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to Race and Performance after Repetition explore how theater and performance studies account for the complex relationship between race and time. Pointing out that repetition has been the primary point of reference for understanding both the complex temporality of theater and the historical persistence of race, they identify and pursue critical alternatives to the conceptualization, organization, measurement, and politics of race in performance. The contributors examine theater, performance art, music, sports, dance, photography, and other forms of performance in topics that range from the movement of boxer Joe Louis and George C. Wolfe's 2016 reimagining of the 1921 all-black musical comedy Shuffle Along to the relationship between dance, mourning, and black adolescence in Flying Lotus's music video "Never Catch Me." Proposing a spectrum of coexisting racial temporalities that are not tethered to repetition, this collection reconsiders central theories in performance studies in order to find new understandings of race.Contributors. Joshua Chambers-Letson, Soyica Diggs Colbert, Nicholas Fesette, Patricia Herrera, Jasmine Elizabeth Johnson, Douglas A. Jones Jr., Mario LaMothe, Jisha Menon, Tavia Nyong'o, Tina Post, Elizabeth W. Son, Shane Vogel, Catherine M. Young, Katherine Zien  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aArts and societyzUnited States. 0aPerforming artsxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPerforming artsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitics and culturezUnited States. 0aRacism and the artszUnited States. 0aRacism in popular culturezUnited States. 0aTheater and societyzUnited States. 0aTimexSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aChambers-Letson, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColbert, Soyica Diggs, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDiggs Colbert, Soyica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g